body:
## Summary

Adds a process to the T&T Server which will listen for Track and Trade state changes on the blockchain, and sync those with the Rethink database. Deltas are maintained by storing multiple versions of each document with a `startBlockNum` and an `endBlockNum`. This allows older versions of documents to be queried, as well as making it possible to walk back forks when they occur.

This closes [#STL-626](https://jira.hyperledger.org/browse/STL-626).

## Steps to Test

This PR is not particularly easy to test, but if you were going to try to, you would:
- Start up a validator
- Start up a REST API (must be on a port other than `8080`)
- Start up the T&T Transaction Processor
- Start up the T&T Server and RethinkDB:
    - cd `families/track_and_trade_server`
    - Make sure you `npm install` and `npm run init`
    - `npm start` (or `rethinkdb` and `nodemon index.js` in separate tabs if start is busted)
- Submit T&T Batches through the REST API . . . somehow (see below)
- Go to `http://localhost:8080/#dataexplorer` in your browser and watch as state magically appears in your database

### JS Testing Script

As of yet, there is no prescribed way to submitting batches to the processor. I used a fairly simple JS script, included below. If you save it in your `families/track_and_trade/server` directory you can run it from the command line by running `npm install request` and then running `node {script name}`. Each run submits one transaction, you can comment in/out whichever transaction payload you want to submit.

```
const request = require('request')
const {BatchEncoder, TransactionEncoder} = require('sawtooth-sdk')
const protos = require('./blockchain/protos')

const privateKey = 'cc12a25efa211177adf6d74a068be3fe55f0949b7b5ba941a9691d67f43643a2'
// const privateKey = '94ab314fde901aa639e04c9d8158244382a001c157652c4b9537672b75ac2c9b'

protos.compile().then(() => {
  const payload = protos.TTPayload.create({
    action: protos.TTPayload.Action.CREATE_AGENT,
    timestamp: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000),
    createAgent: protos.CreateAgentAction.create({name: 'Susan'})
  })

  // const payload = protos.TTPayload.create({
  //   action: protos.TTPayload.Action.CREATE_RECORD_TYPE,
  //   timestamp: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000),
  //   createRecordType: protos.CreateRecordTypeAction.create({
  //     name: 'test',
  //     properties: [protos.PropertySchema.create({
  //       name: 'num',
  //       dataType: protos.PropertySchema.DataType.INT,
  //       required: false
  //     })]
  //   })
  // })

  // const payload = protos.TTPayload.create({
  //   action: protos.TTPayload.Action.CREATE_RECORD,
  //   timestamp: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000),
  //   createRecord: protos.CreateRecordAction.create({
  //     recordId: '123',
  //     recordType: 'test',
  //     properties: [protos.PropertyValue.create({
  //       name: 'num',
  //       dataType: protos.PropertySchema.DataType.INT,
  //       intValue: 42
  //     })]
  //   })
  // })

  // const payload = protos.TTPayload.create({
  //   action: protos.TTPayload.Action.UPDATE_PROPERTIES,
  //   timestamp: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000),
  //   updateProperties: protos.UpdatePropertiesAction.create({
  //     recordId: '123',
  //     properties: [protos.PropertyValue.create({
  //       name: 'num',
  //       dataType: protos.PropertySchema.DataType.INT,
  //       intValue: 64
  //     })]
  //   })
  // })

  const payloadBytes = protos.TTPayload.encode(payload).finish()
  console.log(payloadBytes)
  console.log(protos.TTPayload.decode(payloadBytes))

  const encoder = new TransactionEncoder(privateKey, {
    inputs: ['1c1108'],
    outputs: ['1c1108'],
    familyName: 'track_and_trade',
    familyVersion: '1.0',
    payloadEncoding: 'application/protobuf'
  })

  const txn = encoder.create(payloadBytes)

  const batcher = new BatchEncoder(privateKey)
  const batchBytes = batcher.createEncoded(txn)

  request.post({
    url: 'http://localhost:8008/batches',
    body: batchBytes,
    headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/octet-stream'}
  }, (err, response) => {
    if (err) return console.log(err)
    console.log(response.body)
  })
})

```

Use '''./bin/sawtooth transaction list''' command to show a few general fields of all transactions.
And Use '''./bin/sawtooth transaction list --type /EndpointRegistryTransaction''' to show a few general and specific fields of transactions.

